Demographics with tidycensus

Rick Gilmore

2019-11-04 19:07:10

Purpose

This document describes Rick Gilmores explorations of the tidycensus package. The goal is to determine whether this package can meet some of the needs for demographic visualization and analysis as outlined <demographics-2.0.html>. The package site on GitHub is here: https://github.com/walkerke/tidycensus. This exploration relies heavily on the documentation provided here: https://walkerke.github.io/tidycensus/articles/basic-usage.html.

Set-up

Load tidycensus and associated packages

This document installs tidycensus, tidyverse, ggplot2, and viridis if these are not already installed when the document is knit.

library(tidycensus)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(viridis)

Add Census API key

According to the tidycensus documentation, the following command writes the Census API key to the .Renviron environment variable. for use in future sessions if params$census_api_key is defined in the rmarkdown::render() call to the document. For example, run rmarkdown::render("tidycensus.Rmd", params=list(census_api_key=<YOUR_API_KEY>)) substituting your API key for <YOUR_API_KEY>.

census_api_key(key = params$census_api_key, install = TRUE)

For future runs, execute the following:

readRenviron("~/.Renviron")

Testing functionality

Focus on PA

pa <- get_acs(geography = "county", 
              variables = c(medincome = "B19013_001"), 
              state = "PA")
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS

pa

Wow, super. Lets see if we can generate a map.

pa_county_income <- get_acs(geography = "county", 
                            c(medincome = "B19013_001"), state = "PA", 
                            geometry = TRUE)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
## Downloading feature geometry from the Census website.  To cache shapefiles for use in future sessions, set `options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)`.
## Using FIPS code '42' for state 'PA'
ggplot(pa_county_income) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate), color = NA) + 
  coord_sf(datum = NA) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

Wow again. I wonder if I can filter and show just the counties around Centre County.

Map of Centre County plus surrounding

centre_plus <- "Centre|Clearfield|Clinton|Union|Mifflin|Huntingdon|Blair"

centre_county_plus_income <- pa_county_income %>%
  dplyr::filter(stringr::str_detect(NAME, centre_plus))

centre_county_plus_income %>%
  ggplot(.) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate), color = NA) + 
  coord_sf(datum = NA) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

Sweet. While were here, lets do a local version of the plot with error estimates.

Plot of Centre County plus surrounding median incomes

centre_county_plus_income %>%
  mutate(NAME = gsub(" County, Pennsylvania", "", NAME)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = estimate, y = reorder(NAME, estimate))) +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = estimate - moe, xmax = estimate + moe)) +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Household income by county in Central Pennsylvania",
       subtitle = "2013-2017 American Community Survey",
       y = "",
       x = "ACS estimate (bars represent margin of error)")

Other demographic variables

Lets see if we can use this approach to generate maps and graphs of other demographic variables we are interested in for PLAY.

Spanish speaking

Based on the exploration in <spanish_speaking.Rmd>, Im going to make the following presumptions:

  • American Community Survey (ACS) table B16007 contains info about AGE BY LANGUAGE SPOKEN AT HOME FOR THE POPULATION 5 YEARS AND OVER.

Lets try this for PA as a whole before drilling down.

pa_spanish <- get_acs(geography = "county",
                      c(spanish_18_64 = "B16007_009"), state = "PA",
                        geometry = TRUE)
## Getting data from the 2013-2017 5-year ACS
## Downloading feature geometry from the Census website.  To cache shapefiles for use in future sessions, set `options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE)`.
## Using FIPS code '42' for state 'PA'
pa_spanish %>% 
  ggplot(.) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate), color = NA) + 
  coord_sf(datum = NA) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  ggtitle("Spanish speakers 18-64 years of age")

Next, lets try searching for Speak Spanish in the ACS variables to make sure were on track. This next chunk is copied verbatim from https://walkerke.github.io/tidycensus/articles/basic-usage.html.

v17 <- load_variables(2017, "acs5", cache = TRUE)

View(v17)

Yes, B16007_009 looks like a reasonable table. Lets plot a county-level map and graph like before.

Centre + surrounding counties, Spanish speakers

centre_pa_spanish <- pa_spanish %>% 
  dplyr::filter(stringr::str_detect(NAME, centre_plus))

centre_pa_spanish %>%
  ggplot(.) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate), color = NA) + 
  coord_sf(datum = NA) + 
  theme_minimal() + 
  scale_fill_viridis_c()

centre_pa_spanish %>%
  mutate(NAME = gsub(" County, Pennsylvania", "", NAME)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = estimate, y = reorder(NAME, estimate))) +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = estimate - moe, xmax = estimate + moe)) +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Spanish speakers 18+ years of age by county in Central Pennsylvania",
       subtitle = "2013-2017 American Community Survey",
       y = "",
       x = "ACS estimate (bars represent margin of error)")

So, these data look more like the total population, not the number of Spanish speakers.
